  "prompt": "Why are Indians not referred as \"Asians\", when India is a part of Asia?",
  "response": "There are several reasons for this:\n\n1. Historical Context\n- In the US, \"Asian\" traditionally referred to East Asian populations (Chinese, Japanese, Korean)\n- This was largely due to immigration patterns and historical interactions\n\n2. Cultural Distinctions\n- East Asian and South Asian cultures are quite different\n- People often use more specific terms like \"South Asian\" or \"Indian\" for more precise identification\n\n3. Geographic and Physical Differences\n- People from different parts of Asia have distinct physical characteristics\n- East Asians and South Asians often look different\n\n4. Immigration and Census Categories\n- US Census and demographic categories historically separated \"Asian\" into different sub-groups\n- Only recently have broader, more inclusive definitions emerged\n\n5. Statistical and Social Grouping\n- Academic and social research often distinguishes between different Asian subgroups\n- This helps in understanding specific cultural, economic, and social dynamics\n\n6. Regional Self-Identification\n- Indians themselves often prefer to be called \"Indian\" or \"South Asian\" rather than just \"Asian\"\n\nHowever, in more recent years, there's been a growing recognition that \"Asian\" is an inclusive term that encompasses all people from the Asian continent, including Indians.\n\nThe perception varies by country and context, but generally, the term is becoming more broadly and accurately applied.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
